data.entity_name: Kesavananda Bharati vs State of Kerala
data.content:
Kesavananda Bharati vs State of Kerala
Kesavananda Bharati vs State of Kerala is a landmark constitutional law case from 1973 involving significant rulings regarding the Indian Constitution.

Article 368
Article 368 is a provision in the Indian Constitution that outlines the process for making amendments to the Constitution.

Secularism
Secularism refers to the principle of separating religion from political, social, and educational institutions.

Federalism
Federalism is a system of governance in which power is divided between a central authority and constituent political units.

Judicial Review
Judicial Review is the power of courts to assess whether a law is in compliance with the Constitution.

Separation of Powers
Separation of Powers is a governance model where the legislative, executive, and judiciary branches are distinct and operate independently.

Democracy
Democracy is a system of government in which power is vested in the people, who rule either directly or through freely elected representatives.

Fundamental Rights
Fundamental Rights are a set of rights guaranteed by the Constitution of India that protect individual freedoms and dignity.

Basic Structure Doctrine
The Basic Structure Doctrine is a legal principle that asserts certain fundamental features of the Constitution cannot be altered or destroyed by amendments.

Homosexuality
Homosexuality is the romantic or sexual attraction between members of the same sex, which was decriminalized in India following this ruling.

IPC 377
IPC 377 refers to the specific section of the Indian Penal Code that criminalized homosexual acts prior to its being deemed unconstitutional.

Article 21

Section 377
Section 377 is a provision of the Indian Penal Code that historically criminalized consensual homosexual acts.

LGBTQ
LGBTQ refers to the community of individuals who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer.
